Those words are still there, of course, just not as easily discovered.

I suppose we shouldn't be surprised at this change - all Twitter has, after all, is our data. Restricting access to it opens up opportunities to charge. It also means it's more difficult to discover terrible things we might have said in the past.

Today, I realised the same issue has also impacted Moments, that scrap-booking tool for Tweets, rendering it effectively useless. (I used Moments to gather together all my gifs of a particular film - for example, here's Blade Runner 2049: https://t.co/MzXPwjkirw)
Presumably, I'd need to download this archive again, the next time I needed to access a Tweet which fell outside the jurisdiction of the search.

This implies that this limitation has always been the case, but this is absolutely not true. Support went on to suggest if I was interested in my old Tweets, I could simply download the entire archive of 27 thousand of them.

Twitter search has always been capricious but recently the results have been pathetic, so I raised a bug with Twitter support. Their answer was "Sometimes Tweets older than a week can fail to display because of display limitations."

One of my daft wee pleasures on this site is replying to other people's Tweets with an animated gif from my personal archive. But because these sometimes take a while to upload, I search for them on Twitter, then take the 𝚙𝚒𝚌.𝚝𝚠𝚒𝚝𝚝𝚎𝚛.𝚌𝚘𝚖 URL from my original Tweet.
